AGENT:\
Common ways to find your PostgreSQL username:\
\
1) Default OS user\
- If you\'92re running psql as your current shell user without specifying a username, Postgres will try to use your OS username.\
- Check your shell username:\
  - echo $USER\
  - whoami\
- If you haven\'92t created any DB users, that OS username is likely the default DB user.\
\
2) psql \'97 connect and show current user\
- If you can connect with psql, run:\
  - psql -c "select current_user;"\
  - or, open interactive psql and run: \\conninfo or select current_user;\
- To connect specifying a host/port/database but letting psql use the default user, omit -U. If you need to try a specific user, use -U username.\
\
3) Check service config or startup scripts\
- If Postgres was started via a config or docker compose, the username may be in environment variables:\
  - For Docker Compose: inspect docker-compose.yml for POSTGRES_USER.\
  - For Docker containers: docker inspect or docker-compose config.\
- For system installs, check postgres config or init scripts used when database was created.\
\
4) Look at pg_hba.conf and pg_ident.conf (if access control mapping is used)\
- These files live in the Postgres data directory and may show mappings between OS and DB users.\
\
5) Query the user list (requires access)\
- If you can connect as any superuser, list roles:\
  - psql -c "\\du"\
  - or: SELECT rolname FROM pg_roles;\
\
6) Common defaults\
- On many local installs the DB user is:\
  - The OS user (e.g., your macOS username)\
  - Or explicit 'postgres' user (superuser)\
  - Or a username defined in environment variables like POSTGRES_USER\
\
Examples to try from your shell:\
- whoami\
- psql -c "select current_user;"\
- psql -U postgres -c "\\du"\
- psql -h localhost -p 5432 -c "select current_user;"  (if your server listens on TCP)\
\
